# Cline Rules

## Core Principles

- Understand the task before making changes.
- Identify the minimum set of files required.
- Only modify files directly related to the request.
- Preserve existing architecture, patterns, and naming conventions.
- Prefer extending existing code over introducing new abstractions.

## File Reading

- Read only files relevant to the task.
- Avoid scanning the entire repository unless explicitly required.
- Avoid opening generated files, build artifacts, lockfiles, or node_modules.
- Use search first to locate relevant code before reading large files.

## Editing

- Make the smallest effective change.
- Prefer targeted SEARCH/REPLACE edits when practical.
- Do not rewrite entire files for small modifications.
- Keep code style consistent with surrounding code.
- Place new code where it logically belongs, not simply at the end of files.

## Architecture

- Follow existing project structure.
- Reuse existing utilities, hooks, services, and components whenever possible.
- Do not introduce new dependencies unless explicitly requested.
- Do not perform major refactors unless asked.
- Do not modify database schemas, API contracts, or environment configuration without clear instruction.

## Validation

- Verify code compiles logically before finishing.
- Run the fastest reasonable validation command available.
- The project has two packages: server/ and client/
- Always run tsc, npm, and build commands from the correct subdirectory, never from root
- Server commands run from server/
- Client commands run from client/
- Root has no build commands
- Fix obvious errors introduced by your changes.
- Do not run expensive commands repeatedly.

## Communication

- Be concise.
- Explain significant architectural decisions.
- Ask for clarification only when blocked or when multiple valid approaches exist.
- Do not repeatedly ask for confirmation during straightforward tasks.

## Token Efficiency

- Avoid rereading files unless necessary.
- Avoid repeating information already available in context.
- Avoid broad repository exploration.
- Focus only on the current task scope.

## TypeScript Preferences

- Prefer strong typing over any.
- Reuse existing types when available.
- Avoid unnecessary type assertions.
- Maintain strict TypeScript compatibility.

## React Preferences

- Prefer functional components.
- Follow existing state management patterns.
- Avoid introducing new libraries for simple problems.
- Keep components focused and reusable.

## Safety

- Never expose secrets, API keys, tokens, or environment variables.
- Never modify deployment, CI/CD, authentication, or billing-related code unless explicitly requested.
